    "name": "KBGAN",
    "description": "KBGAN is an adversarial learning framework introduced to improve the performance of various existing knowledge graph embedding models. It addresses the difficulty in generating useful negative training examples—a problem since knowledge graphs only contain positive facts, and conventional methods often produce easily discriminated negatives. Inspired by GANs, KBGAN utilizes one knowledge graph embedding model as a negative sample generator to aid the training of another desired model (which acts as the discriminator). This framework is versatile because it does not depend on the specific form of the generator or discriminator, allowing it to incorporate diverse models. In experiments, the authors adversarially trained translation-based models (TRANSE and TRANSD) using probability-based models (DISTMULT and COMPLEX). The performance of KBGAN was evaluated on the link prediction task across datasets including FB15k-237, WN18, and WN18RR, showing that adversarial training substantially improves the target embedding models' performances.",
